Shadowmere is the ruin of a state project: a frontier march-town founded to extend Midgaard's law, logistics, and burial order into unstable territory northwest of the city.
Its mandate was practical: guard transit, tax and classify goods, process war dead and plague dead before they reached core city districts, keep records admissible in Midgaard tribunals.
The Plague Mandate granted emergency powers without sunset provisions: rapid intake, forced quarantines, immediate cremation authority, and suspension of lineage appeals. Temporary authority became permanent.
After plague peaks receded, four power blocs deadlocked over rollback: Crown envoys demanding restored noble precedence, Compact wardens insisting containment powers remain, temple delegates seeking release rites for mass graves, march commanders refusing to relinquish emergency chains of command.
The Last Bell Crisis: three contradictory decrees — amnesty, lockdown, and requisition — rang in one night. Garrisons split. Chapel courts split. Necromantic expedients once justified as temporary containment were repurposed for political continuity.
Five factions now occupy the ruin: the Oathbound March (undead soldiers enforcing obsolete orders), the Crimson Household (aristocratic regime claiming continuity through bloodline custody of estate charters), the Binder Collegium (necromancer-clerks treating souls as entries requiring categorization), the Gallows Syndicate (execution and toxin specialists), and Fen-Adapted Remnants (non-humanoid populations in floodplains and blackwater channels).
Blight hydrology: original runoff was routed through controlled channels tied to burial and quarantine districts. During crisis years, alchemical disposal, blood sacrifice residues, and preservative salts were introduced into the same system. Sealed crypts flooded from below; low fields became permanent toxic wetlands.
The blight is not accidental corruption but infrastructure memory: the channels that were supposed to contain the dead now sustain the wetland ecology that replaced ordered governance.
Shadowmere is a frontier mirror of Midgaard's own institutional tensions: record supremacy, containment bureaucracy, emergency drift, and memory conflict all appear here in harsher and more consequential form.
Every faction invokes law. None can establish uncontested legitimacy. Contradictory records in Shadowmere can all be technically valid yet mutually destructive.
Architecture progresses as procedure: intake to classification to confinement to transformation to disposal to appeal denied.
For Midgaard scholars, Shadowmere is a warning archive — proof that lawful systems become predatory when emergency powers lose limits.

